|CKBStreet Samurai Firmware|000

|CK0The Cortex OS hosts every Street Samurai routine. Firmware needs an active
contract, an installed Cortex OS, the required Guild Level, enough SP,
acceptable Heat, and any paired signature implant. Edge is normally an optional
amplifier rather than an activation requirement. Samskills reports readiness;
samhelp <routine> explains the command's intended use and interactions.|000

|CKBExecution cycle|000
|CK0Active routines have no separate long cooldowns. A successful activation
uses the shared Cortex execution cycle and Darkwind's normal damage or support
action pacing. Persistent effects generally cannot be activated again while
their existing instance remains online.|000

|CKBActive and passive firmware|000
|CK0Active firmware is deployed with a command. Passive firmware comes online
automatically when its Guild Level and required hardware are present. Passive
systems appear in samskills even though they do not have activation commands.
Dashboard and the combat monitor show whether many of those systems are active
or ready.|000

|CKBNotable interactions|000
|CK0Threat Scan reports a target's armour and resistances. Ripcut consumes its
lock for a stronger armour-piercing strike. Photon Lance calibrates its
wavelength from the lock, Micro-Missile Swarm adds a guided missile, and
deployed Monowire reads the lock without consuming it. Most active routines
automatically route one available Edge into a stronger version of their normal
effect. Damaging Photon Lance and Micro-Missile Swarm executions also generate
Edge. Specialized routines can route more or spend it only when a particular
response occurs.|000

|CK0Overclock creates temporary thermal headroom and improves movement and
attack response, but every activation stresses the Cortex OS. Cortex Rank
improves its duration, avoidance response, and thermal headroom. Armor Weave
turns Dermal Plating into persistent shielding whose strength and thermal load
follow Guild Level, Cortex Rank, grade, and condition. When the shield collapses
it creates another Heat burst and produces Edge.|000

|CK0Smart Smoke and Jammer Field solve different defensive problems. Smart
Smoke is personal physical cover: it strongly disrupts ranged attacks aimed at
the operator and offers only modest protection in melee. It can be deployed
before a fight. Jammer Field is active battlefield control: it suppresses the
outgoing damage of hostiles fighting the operator or nearby party members and
periodically desynchronizes one attack swing. It protects the team by degrading
hostiles rather than making the operator harder to target.|000

|CK0Signal Shroud supplies the operator's passive dodge telemetry. Jammer Node
instead reserves additional SP bandwidth for interference firmware. Edge adds
a real point of Smart Smoke cover. In Jammer Field it strengthens suppression,
accelerates the desynchronization pulse, and extends field duration.|000

|CK0Ghoststep and Zero Signal solve different pressure states. Ghoststep is an
in-fight reposition: it keeps the primary target engaged, drops secondary
attackers and hunts, and arms the Reflex Lattice to improve avoidance against
the next incoming attack sequence. Zero Signal is the full escape routine: it
erases current combat and hunts, rejects remote tracking or scrying locks, and
uses the Ghost Circuit to mask a limited number of attempts to start combat
again. Ghost Circuit grade establishes that reacquisition capacity, while
Cortex Rank expands it over continued progression.|000

|CK0Monowire deploys as an unbreakable weapon for thirty minutes. It adjusts to
the operator's combat progression and remains useful with different weapon
loadouts. Threat Scan guides additional armour-piercing cuts, monowire edge
arms a stronger breach, and Second Spur can join that breach.|000

|CKBRequired hardware|000
|CK0Every routine depends on the Cortex OS. Neonwake, Snap Cut, Jolt,
Overclock, Ripcut, and the Ronin-sama Kernel use the Cortex as primary
hardware. Other firmware also requires the following paired implant:|000

|CK0Threat Scan - Photon Targeting Suite
Photon Lance - Photon Targeting Suite
Armor Weave - Dermal Plating
Smart Smoke - Signal Shroud
Ghoststep - Reflex Lattice
Trauma Buffer - Trauma Buffer Node
Monowire - Monofilament Spur
Jammer Field - Jammer Node
Micro-Missile Swarm - Dorsal Tempest Driver
Nanomend - Repair Coprocessor
Predictive Sight - Predictive Coprocessor
Cold Signal - Thermal Exchange Manifold
Thermal Purge - Thermal Exchange Manifold
Zero Signal - Ghost Circuit
Second Spur - Second Spur
Overdrive - Overdrive Module
Chrome Tempest - Dorsal Tempest Driver|000

|CK0Some optional hardware strengthens a routine without being required. Blade
hardware supports Snap Cut and Ripcut; reflex hardware supports Jolt and
Overclock. Samskills reports only missing required hardware, so use dashboard
or implants when checking optional enhancements.|000

|CKBWhat changes effectiveness|000
|CK0Hardware grade improves the firmware paired with that implant. Cortex Rank
gradually improves host throughput. Character capabilities and current Heat
shape combat routines where relevant. Low integrity or high fragmentation weakens
the affected hardware and poor Cortex condition can influence the entire
platform. These factors work together, but maintenance never makes a routine
completely useless.|000

|CKBFailures and readiness|000
|CK0Read the command's failure message first. Samstatus checks contract, Edge,
Heat, and the Cortex cycle. Samskills checks Guild Level and required hardware.
Dashboard checks the Cortex, implant condition, active effects, strain, and
maintenance alerts. An invalid target, an existing copy of an effect, normal
room safeguards, or insufficient SP can also reject a command.|000
